One thing I would add

Here’s a variable I don’t think we’ve discussed before that fits your framework:

Affordance

Every concept advertises what it allows you to do.

Fire
affordances:
    warmth
    cooking
    metallurgy
    destruction
    signaling

Or:

Trust
affordances:
    delegation
    cooperation
    vulnerability
    coordination

Humans are remarkably good at perceiving affordances in the physical world—seeing a chair as “something to sit on” rather than just an object. We don’t have an equally explicit way of representing the affordances of ideas.

A cognitive universe that surfaced affordances directly would encourage a shift from:

“What is this?”

to:

“What does this make possible?”

That fits remarkably well with the Pantheon’s emphasis on operators, missions, and transformations. It treats knowledge not as static descriptions but as latent capabilities waiting to be activated.